answers.body_markdown:
Recursion is indeed the answer, but not recursion among the strings in the result set, but recursion along the characters within a result string. 

Put in a less abstract way: All result strings of length n can be formed by taking a result string of length n-1, and appending a possible last character.

In code:

    List&lt;String&gt; generateStrings(String[][] possibleCharacters, int index) {
        if (index &lt; 0) {
            return new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(&quot;&quot;);
        } else {
            var results = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();
            for (var s : generateStrings(possibleCharacters, index - 1)) {
                for (var c : possibleCharacters[index]) {
                    results.add(s + c);
                }
            }
            return results;
        }
    }

Efficiency purists would frown on the repeated String concatenations. To avoid that, we can use a single `StringBuilder` to build all Strings:

	void generateStrings(String[][] possibleCharacters, StringBuilder prefix, List&lt;String&gt; results) {
	    var index = prefix.length();
	    if (index == possibleCharacters.length) {
	        results.add(prefix.toString());
	    } else {
	        for (String c : possibleCharacters[index]) {
	          prefix.append(c);
	          generateStrings(possibleCharacters, prefix, results);
	          prefix.delete(index, prefix.length());
	        }
	    }
	}

Another possible problem is that the list of generated strings gets really big really quick, so storing them all in memory before processing them might be considered wasteful. In phython, you&#39;d use a generator for that. In Java, the closest semantic equivalent would be a `Stream`, but they are hard to provide, so a simple callback is probably the better choice. That is, rather than passing a `List&lt;String&gt;` to receive the results, you&#39;d pass a `Consumer&lt;String&gt;` that is to be invoked for every result.

